[Student "W"]
{[showcards W:CQ]

You are East. The bidding has been as shown.

You lead the \CQ, West plays low and North wins the \CA.

North pulls trumps in 2 rounds. He then takes the \DK, \DQ, \DA, discarding a \H on the last one. Next he plays dummy's last \C to his \CK.

Having done all this, North now plays a low \H from his hand. What do you play?

Play the \HA.

If you followed what North was doing you will realize that he has eliminated both the \Ds and \Cs from both his hand and dummy. If it isn't clear that he is now out of \Cs, just remember the bidding - he must have had 5 \Ss and 4 \Hs.

Suppose you play low on this \H (as North hopes you will). Dummy's \HK will take the trick, and when another \H is played you will have to win it with your now bare \HA. You will then have to play a \D or a \C, giving North a ruff and sluff.

But if you take your \HA now, then exit with your \H2, North can win the \HK but will still have to lose a \H to West.}
[Play "W"]CQ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:A6.AK965.JT5.QT2 KQJ95..9642.9653 T72.J8732.AKQ.AK 843.QT4.873.J874"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H pass 3D pass 3NT pass 6H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "2ba61aef2d762e7370875bc5bf723ead1ad304c444e27437a67a09f9d72f29a0"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/second_hand_play"]
[Student "E"]
{[showcards N:HJ]

You are North. The bidding has been as shown.

South led the \SK, won by East's \SA. East played a small \C to dummy's \CA, then led dummy's \HJ.

What do you play? \HQ or \H4? 

Play the \H4.

Remember that East opened 1\H, so he has 5 of them. With only 3 trumps out he has no intention of finessing. Perhaps he led the \HJ just to tempt you to cover in this situation.

If you play low he will win with one of his high \Hs and then you will have a sure \H winner. Along with the \S winner South has you will defeat the slam.

If you cover the \HJ with your \HQ East will again win with one of his high ones. But now the position will be clear to East and he will return to dummy and play another \H, finessing your \H10. With no trump loser he will make the slam. }
[Play "W"]SK

